National Security Chairperson Peter Mwathi at Parliament, Nairobi. [David Njaaga, Standard]  US military experts and their Kenyan counterparts yesterday held a joint drill where they conducted mock terror attacks and staged appropriate responses.  Using sophisticated military hardware, the two sides imitated terror attacks in the operation at Rossyln Academy in Nairobi.  The operation dubbed Joint Readiness Exercise was conducted by a highly trained Special Programme for Embassy Augmentation and Response team (SPEAR) consisting of security officers and emergency response team.  Three hundred people participated in the exercise, including local hospital staff and bomb squad.  US, Kenya to conduct joint security drill at Gigiri  South Korea carries out security drill  Emergency drills should be conducted more regularly  Is a security drill really necessary if it will result to loss of life? “We are prepared and ready though you can never be too prepared that’s why it is important to do exercise regularly, to train together regularly and to simulate the emergency situation,” said embassy spokesman Andrew Veveiros  This is the sixth mock exercise conducted by Kenya and the US.  “I appreciate the involvement of US and UK in the war against terror in Kenya and I believe we are prepared. They were helping us in terms of the budget,” said Peter Mwathi, chairman of the National Assembly Committee on National Security.      Strathmore University has defended their actions in security drill that left one dead  Was the Strathmore security drill properly carried out? Here is what it should have achieved.  Advocate Ngumbau Mutua faults Strathmore University over terror attack drill that turned chaotic By Stephen Nzioka | 3 hours ago By Stephen Rutto | 15 hours ago By Micah Sali | 15 hours ago By Lynn Kolongei | 16 hours ago